Currently there is a larger degree of emphasis on reducing network latency due to the minimal proving times miners have optimized to on those circuits. We absolutely will provide time for all to test and review before finney but the way this variable is used changes

Today, miners receive requests in batches. So a validator prepares a request for each miner, then queries all of them, maintaining a concurrent connection limit of 16 while doing so (effectively processing in chunks)

If we were to increase that to 32, validators _may_ operate faster* and load on miners _may_ be increased
* if their hardware does not limit them
However, the validator's loop has been meaningfully updated away from the aforementioned request logic

We need to send out individual requests to miners and continuously provide a continual load rather than having validators query all of the miners, verify all responses and loop back. For external requests, switching the architecture to a single request based approach where 32 requests are in-flight at all times allows for very fast responses through validator RPC endpoints (~400s -> 33s in some cases).
This is a very necessary change not just for external queries but for the future of Omron
Changing the requests from batch to in-flight will improve response speed (which is what your new code is doing). It has nothing to do with changing the concurrency from 16 to 32.
If the concurrency is doubled, the existing miners might get deregistered after the upgrade, causing them losses.
Any increase or decrease in load is uniform

They are the incentives for miners directly. The flow is as follows
- Validators evaluate a batch of 256 requests through the proof system
- Every 4th evaluation, validators request proofs covering the previous 1024 evaluations, then commit these proofs through our proof publishing system to AR.IO which settles on the Arweave blockchain, embedding these proofs into the permaweb.
- Periodically, validators will set weights (based on the set weights rate limit hyperparameter) and will use the most recent scores as these weights. At this step, weights are technically re-normalized to sum to 1, but this has no impact.
- The blockchain calculates consensus incentive values, based on the submitted weights across all validators, weighted by stake.

SN2 isn’t in use by the render network at the current time however these kinds of use cases are something the SN2 can and will support over time. 

Verification is crucial for applications like these where outputs are produced from a decentralized set of actors lending their resources out, as node operators are inherently incentivized to do less work if they can receive the same reward. Due to the scale and size of jobs in networks like these (a high number of low value jobs) an automated dispute resolution system is required. In this case, probabilistic models can be used to determine the likelihood that a given job was completed correctly (e.g. a low fidelity thumbnail frame compared to a fully rendered & high resolution frame). The question then comes down to who runs the model at scale? Is that party a trusted party? This is where Inference Labs and SN2 come in. By providing a zero knowledge proof which attests to the probabilistic evaluation process and provides a guarantee that the process hasn’t been tampered with, network participants receive a verifiable record that indicates the quality of their output as defined by the network. This provides enhanced transparency, allowing any network participant to understand why a given action was taken based on their outputs (for example a deregistration or slash). This also enhances privacy of the protocol, as the intellectual property of the output verification mechanism itself can remain hidden, preventing gaming of the mechanism.

SN2 is designed to support a variety of use cases and we’d love to support any community additions to the current set of circuits live today. If you’d like to implement a circuit on SN2, please see our comprehensive guide, here: https://github.com/inference-labs-inc/omron-subnet/blob/main/docs/custom_circuit_integrations.md
